"{\"uid\": \"si.com-college-tcu-basketball-women-s-basketball-van-lith-wins-bronze-at-paris-olympics-01j4mhc5ytwb\", \"text\": \"In this story:  Hailey Van Lith made history in Paris.\\u00c2  Van Lith, a transfer from LSU and graduate student on the TCU women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s basketball team, became the first Horned Frog basketball player to win an Olympic medal. She helped Team USA earn bronze in the 3x3 competition at the Olympic Games Paris. This is Van Lith\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s seventh FIBA medal.\\u00c2  Over the course of 10 games, Van Lith led Team USA in cumulative scoring and was the only active collegian competing for USA Basketball in 5-on-5 or 3x3.\\u00c2  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI am most proud of us for this last game because we went from getting our gold medal dreams crushed to having two hours to turn around and play one of the best teams in the tournament in Canada,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Van Lith said in a release on gofrogs.com. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThat game was all about mental toughness. And we really got it together. We showed mental toughness. And we won ourselves a bronze medal.\\\"  Our Olympian \\u00f0\\u009f\\u0092\\u009c#GoFrogs|#Olympicspic.twitter.com/6EIRzgIRJc  Van Lith scored a team-high six points on 5-of-7 shooting in the medal-securing, 16-13 defeat of Canada. Team USA won six of its final seven games to nab a second consecutive medal. The team took gold at the 2020 Tokyo Games.\\u00c2  Victories over Spain, France, Canada and China (twice) propelled Team USA to the medal round after dropping the first three games. Spain won the semifinal rematch 18-16 in overtime and ultimately took silver, finishing second to Germany.\\u00c2  Van Lith arrived at TCU in April after one season at LSU and three seasons at Louisville where she averaged 14.5 points, four rebounds and 2.8 assists per game.\\u00c2  Want to join the discussion?\\u00c2Click here\\u00c2\\u00a0to become a member of the Killer Frogs message board community today!Follow KillerFrogs on Twitter\\u00c2\\u00a0to stay up to date on all the latest TCU news! Follow KillerFrogs on\\u00c2Facebook\\u00c2\\u00a0and\\u00c2Instagram\\u00c2\\u00a0as well. Download the KillerFrogs app on Google Play or in the Apple App Store.  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Tori Couch writes about TCU women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s basketball and football for KillerFrogs. She started covering TCU sports while serving as sports editor for TCU360 (TCU\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s student media outlet) over a decade ago. Since then, she has worked as an academic advisor in two Division I athletic departments, covered high school sports and written stories for the Cotton Bowl game program and Reddit CFB. Her portfolio includes coverage of Big 12 championships, FCS national title games, the College Football Playoffs, Bedlam (Oklahoma-Oklahoma State football) and the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s NCAA basketball tournament. Tori graduated from TCU in 2014 and now resides in Fort Worth with her husband and daughter.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"